  <h1>How Retaliation Claims Work</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>The three elements</h2><p>(1) Protected activity: the employee engaged in legally protected conduct. (2) Materially adverse action: the employer took an action that would dissuade a reasonable employee from engaging in protected activity (<em>Burlington Northern v. White</em>, 2006). (3) Causation: the protected activity caused the adverse action.</p>
  <h2>Materially adverse — broader than termination</h2><p>After <em>Burlington Northern</em>, retaliation covers any action that would deter reasonable employees: demotions, pay cuts, negative performance reviews, shift changes to less desirable hours, exclusion from training opportunities, increased scrutiny, and hostile work environment following a complaint. Courts do not require economic harm for every retaliation claim.</p>
  <h2>Causation standards</h2><p>Title VII retaliation: but-for causation (<em>University of Texas v. Nassar</em>, 2013). FLSA retaliation: but-for. Workers&rsquo; comp retaliation: many states use motivating factor or substantial factor standards (more plaintiff-favorable). Evidence of causation: temporal proximity, cat&rsquo;s paw theory (biased supervisor influenced the decision-maker), inconsistent explanations for the adverse action.</p>
  <h2>Damages by statute</h2><p>Title VII: capped comp/punitive + uncapped back pay/front pay + attorney fees. FLSA: back pay × 2 (liquidated damages) + attorney fees. Section 1981: uncapped compensatory and punitive. OSHA: reinstatement, back pay, attorney fees. FCA: 2× back pay + attorney fees for whistleblowers.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/types-of-retaliation">types of retaliation</a> and <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-retaliatory-firing">what to do after retaliatory firing</a>.</p>
